        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-container">
            <h3>Can inflation be a negative percentage?</h3>
            <p>Yes. When the inflation rate drops below 0%, it is called Deflation. During deflationary periods, money gains purchasing power and general retail prices drop. While it sounds great for consumers, aggressive deflation often signals severe economic depressions.</p>
            
            <h3>What is a good or "normal" inflation rate?</h3>
            <p>Most central banks around the world, particularly the Federal Reserve, target an annual inflation rate of approximately 2%. This provides enough price plasticity to encourage consumer spending while maintaining currency stability.</p>
            
            <h3>Does inflation affect mortgage debt?</h3>
            <p>Usually, inflation benefits individuals holding heavy fixed-rate debt like mortgages. Because your <a href="/calculator/emi-calculator">EMI Calculator</a> locks you into a fixed payment, you are paying back the bank with "cheaper" depreciated dollars years into the future.</p>
        </div>

